===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}}: leaves growing from a tree. Original form of {{och-l|葉|leaf}}. Later phonetically borrowed as an instance of {{liushu|j|nocap=y}} to represent {{och-l|枼|flat}}.

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' mistakes it for a compound.

===Etymology 1===
{{lang|zh|枼}} and characters derived from it represent the phonetic series *''lep'' with the root meanings of “flat, wide, thin”. Members from this word family possibly include:
* {{och-l|葉|leaf}}
* {{och-l|鰈|flatfish, plaice}}
* {{och-l|楪}} > {{och-l|碟|plate}}
* {{och-l|牒|official document < plank}}.
* {{och-l|蝶|butterfly}} > {{och-l|蝴蝶|tr=*ɡaː l'eːb}}

Compare with the Middle Korean:
* {{m|okm|나븨|t=butterfly|tr=napuy}} (modern {{m|ko|나비}})
* {{m|okm|닢|t=leaf|tr=niph}} (modern {{m|ko|잎}})
* {{m|okm|넙치|t=flatfish|tr=nepchi}},

These are likewise derived from the similarly shaped adjective root {{m|okm|넙다|tr=nepta|t=to be wide, flat}} (modern {{m|ko|넓다}}).

See {{zh-l|蝴蝶}} for more information.

